13/10/2006
PODGORICA, Montenegro -- Southeast European interior ministers gathered on Thursday (October 12th) for a two-day meeting in the Montenegrin town of Budva. 
The focus was on progress achieved in the common fight against all types of organised crime, as well as on possible enhancement of regional and trans-border co-operation in the field. 
Representatives from Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Macedonia, Montenegro, Serbia and Slovenia participated.
In other news Thursday, Montenegrin President Filip Vujanovic visited Slovenia for talks with counterpart Janez Drnovsek. 
Both expressed their readiness to expand bilateral co-operation, and Slovenia offered to assist Montenegro's EU integration efforts and its bid to join NATO's Partnership for Peace programme. 
(Pobjeda, Vijesti - 13/10/06; MINA, PBS - 12/10/06)
